package:
  source: https://crates.io
  name: anes
  version: 0.1.6
  revision: 378ac7461ecac29fde9e10df7b08359d1315a9ad
  digest: Q86nRQxGYFuIXQ-guDMKmEwy3UNFe28LB-ZwGkqMCjU
review:
  thoroughness: medium
  understanding: high
  rating: neutral
issues:
- id: arrow-key-modifiers-ignored
  severity: medium
  comment: |
    `Parser` returns `KeyModifiers::empty()` for standard xterm
    cursor-key-with-modifier sequences (`ESC[1;5A` for Ctrl+Up,
    `ESC[1;2A` for Shift+Up, etc.). Root cause:
    `parse_csi_arrow_key_modifiers` indexes the wrong parameter
    and then `saturating_sub(48)` the already-numeric value as if
    it were an ASCII digit. No memory or safety impact; just
    wrong output for a feature the crate advertises.
    Reproduction: repros/anes/0.1.6/arrow-key-modifiers-ignored/
comment: |-
  ANSI escape-sequence provider + parser, ~3k LOC of pure Rust. Read
  every .rs file under src/, plus Cargo.toml, README, all integration
  tests, and the examples.
  
  Supply-chain surface:
    - No build.rs.
    - No proc-macro (Cargo.toml has no `proc-macro = true`).
    - One optional dep: bitflags 1.2 (only for the `parser` feature).
    - No `unsafe` in src/. The only `unsafe` is in examples/parser.rs
      around libc::tcsetattr / cfmakeraw — examples aren't published.
    - No I/O, no network, no env-var reads. Sequences are just `Display`
      impls; the parser is a pure byte->state-machine.
  
  Concern #2 / #3 (unsafe): N/A — no `unsafe` ships in the library.
  
  Concern #4 (correctness): one real bug found.
  
  `parse_csi_arrow_key_modifiers` in src/parser/parsers.rs:65-67 is
  inert for real-world input. It is called as
  `parse_csi_arrow_key_modifiers(parameters.first().cloned())` for
  CSI A/B/C/D (cursor keys). For the standard xterm modifier sequence
  `ESC [ 1 ; <m> <letter>`, `parameters.first()` is the cursor-key id
  (always 1), not the modifier. The function then applies
  `saturating_sub(48)` to that integer — as if it were an ASCII digit —
  producing 0, which maps to `KeyModifiers::empty()`. Net effect:
  Shift/Ctrl/Alt+Arrow are silently dropped.
  
  The crate's own test (`tests/parser/key.rs:40` `csi_arrow_key_modifiers`)
  hides this by using non-standard inputs `\x1B[50A` and `\x1B[53A`,
  which only "work" because 50-48=2 and 53-48=5. No terminal emits
  those.
  
  Repro: repros/anes/0.1.6/arrow-key-modifiers-ignored/
  
  Minor notes (not rating-impacting):
    - Engine accumulates u64 params with `saturating_mul(10)` /
      `saturating_add` — good defensive choice.
    - `parse_csi_xterm_mouse` does `parameters[1] as u8` and column/row
      `as u16` truncating casts. Mouse-protocol values fit in those
      widths per spec; no exploitability.
    - `Parser::advance` writes `idx < len - 1 || more` inside the
      `enumerate` loop body. `len - 1` is only evaluated when the loop
      iterates, so an empty buffer is fine.
  
  Rating: neutral — the cursor-key modifier path is a documented
  feature (per the function name and the test) that does not work
  against real terminal input. Crate is still useful for the
  sequence-generation side (the Display impls) and for the rest of
  the parser (CSI tilde keys, mouse, cursor position, UTF-8).
----- SIGN CREV PROOF -----
