comment: |-
  Widely used fixed-capacity vector/string crate by bluss. Read every .rs file
  under src/ (lib.rs, arrayvec.rs, arrayvec_impl.rs, array_string.rs, char.rs,
  errors.rs, utils.rs), plus Cargo.toml(.orig), README, and the CI workflow.
  
  Concern 1 (malicious code): clean. No build.rs, no proc-macros, no
  include_bytes!, no obfuscation, no network/FS I/O, no shelling out. Optional
  deps (serde, borsh, zeroize) are reputable and gated behind features. License
  and repository metadata match upstream.
  
  Concern 2 (unsafe without SAFETY): the crate makes heavy use of `unsafe`
  (around 30 blocks/functions across arrayvec.rs, array_string.rs, char.rs,
  arrayvec_impl.rs). Only one block carries a `// SAFETY:` comment
  (array_string.rs:147 in `zero_filled`); a handful of `///`-level doc comments
  partially document unsafe fn invariants (char.rs:30, arrayvec.rs:667,
  arrayvec.rs:1075). The remainder rely on the reader inferring invariants
  from surrounding code. The patterns themselves mirror std::Vec
  (MaybeUninit buffer, BackshiftOnDrop in retain, ScopeExitGuard in extend,
  Drain truncating len before yielding, ZST-aware raw_ptr_add) and look
  correct, but per the rubric this caps the rating at `neutral`.
  
  Concern 3 (miri): miri runs in CI via .github/workflows/ci.yml (`cargo miri
  test --all-features`), exercising the safe-API tests against the unsafe
  internals. No penalty.
  
  Concern 4 (correctness): walked the load-bearing unsafe paths (push,
  try_insert, retain, drain_range, extend_from_iter, IntoIter/Drain Drop,
  into_inner_unchecked, try_extend_from_slice, try_push_str). Bounds checks
  and len updates are placed correctly relative to writes/drops; panic-safety
  guards set len before running user code; range Bounds use saturating_add to
  avoid overflow; ZST handling is explicit. Did not find a reproducible bug.
  
  Rating capped at `neutral` solely due to missing SAFETY comments
  (concern #2); functional code quality is otherwise high.
