comment: |-
  Proc-macro crate by David Tolnay that desugars `async fn` in traits into
  methods returning `Pin<Box<dyn Future + Send + 'async_trait>>`, providing
  the dyn-compatible variant the language doesn't deliver natively.
  
  Inspection:
  - Cargo.toml: `proc-macro = true`, `build = false`, `exclude = ["build.rs"]`.
    No build.rs present. Dependencies are syn, quote, proc-macro2 — the
    standard dtolnay proc-macro stack — pinned to recent minor versions.
  - Read every .rs file under src/: lib.rs (entry), args.rs, parse.rs,
    bound.rs, lifetime.rs, receiver.rs, expand.rs, verbatim.rs. All pure
    AST munging via syn::visit_mut and quote!. No I/O, no env access, no
    process spawning, no obfuscation. The `unsafe` tokens grep finds are
    syn::Token![unsafe] used to parse `unsafe trait`/`unsafe impl` from
    the user's input (parse.rs:14-16), not unsafe blocks.
  - Generated code path: expand.rs emits `Box::pin(async move { ... })`
    and `Pin<Box<dyn Future<Output = _> + Send + 'async_trait>>` — pure
    safe Rust. README confirms "no use of `unsafe` in the expanded code".
  - CI (.github/workflows/ci.yml): matrix across stable/beta/nightly and
    MSRV 1.56/1.75, `cargo miri test` with `-Zmiri-strict-provenance`,
    clippy pedantic, docs build, minimal-versions check.
  
  Concerns #1-#3 all clear: no malicious patterns, zero unsafe code,
  miri runs anyway. Concern #4: nothing jumped out — this is mature,
  one of the most depended-upon proc-macros on crates.io.
