package:
  source: https://crates.io
  name: bcrypt
  version: 0.19.0
  revision: 9222c285cad733610459f5fb5453b92bdd4b31f4
  digest: ZHTcKX-t6DO3pRtVOXQSrV7oQ_Pbyf3f2m1RhuyICDo
review:
  thoroughness: medium
  understanding: high
  rating: neutral
issues:
- id: panic-on-non-ascii-hash
  severity: medium
  comment: |
    `verify(_, hash)` panics when given a 60-byte `&str` whose `$..$..$`
    prefix is valid but which contains a multi-byte UTF-8 character that
    straddles byte index 29. `split_hash` (src/lib.rs:220, 223) does
    `&salt_and_hash[..22]` without enforcing that bytes 7..60 are ASCII.
    Denial-of-service if untrusted input flows into `verify`; no memory
    safety impact (`#![forbid(unsafe_code)]`).
    Reproduction: repros/bcrypt/0.19.0/panic-on-non-ascii-hash/
comment: |-
  Read every file: Cargo.toml, README, src/lib.rs (752 lines), src/bcrypt.rs,
  src/errors.rs. No build.rs (`build = false` in Cargo.toml), no proc-macros,
  no `unsafe` (crate is `#![forbid(unsafe_code)]`). Dependencies are all
  reputable: base64 0.22, blowfish 0.9, getrandom 0.4 (optional), subtle
  2.4.1, zeroize 1.5.4 (optional), quickcheck (dev). Crypto delegated to
  blowfish; OrpheanBeholderScryDoubt magic and EksBlowfish key-schedule are
  the standard bcrypt construction. Constant-time compare via `subtle` in
  `_verify`. Password buffer zeroized after hashing when `zeroize` feature
  is on.
  
  Concern #4 (functional correctness): found a panic in `split_hash`
  (lib.rs:220, 223). The function checks `hash.len() == 60` and that bytes
  0/3/6 are `$`, then does `&salt_and_hash[..22]` / `&salt_and_hash[22..]`
  on a `&str` without validating the rest is ASCII. A 60-byte hash whose
  prefix is `$2a$04$` and which contains a multi-byte UTF-8 character
  straddling byte index 29 (e.g. `£` at byte 28-29) panics in the
  `str::Index` impl with "byte index 22 is not a char boundary". The
  existing `does_no_error_on_char_boundary_splitting` test attempts to
  cover this but its input fails the prefix check before reaching the
  slice, so the test is inert. Repro at
  repros/bcrypt/0.19.0/panic-on-non-ascii-hash/. Real bcrypt hashes are
  always ASCII so this only matters when untrusted UTF-8 reaches `verify`;
  hence the rating cap at `neutral` per the rubric for "panics on plausible
  input". No memory-safety impact (unsafe is forbidden).
  
  Suggested fix: validate `hash.is_ascii()` early, or perform the slicing on
  `hash.as_bytes()` and only `from_utf8` the digit/version slices.
----- SIGN CREV PROOF -----
