  in consts.rs (SIGMA + IV) match the BLAKE2 RFC 7693 spec.
  
  Cap: rating limited to `neutral` because every unsafe block lacks a
  `// SAFETY:` comment (grep for "SAFETY" returns no matches). The unsafe
  is mostly defensible — as_bytes.rs::from_raw_parts is gated by an
  `unsafe trait Safe` marker implemented only for POD primitives and
  repr(C)/repr(simd) wrappers; the SIMD intrinsics in simdop/simdint/
  simd_opt are gated behind the off-by-default nightly `simd` feature
  (also uses removed `feature(platform_intrinsics)` + legacy `asm!`
  syntax, so that path almost certainly no longer builds on current
  nightly). Default build (`std`) only hits the as_bytes.rs unsafe.
  Still, the lack of SAFETY comments is the documented cap trigger.
  
  Miri: .crate tarball doesn't ship CI config; the SIMD/asm paths aren't
  miri-testable anyway (intrinsics + inline asm). The default-feature
  unsafe (from_raw_parts over POD slices) would be miri-testable but
  this can't be verified from the tarball alone.
  
  Correctness: counter `self.t: u64` and `t1 = 0` for BLAKE2b technically
  caps messages at 2^64 bytes vs. spec's 2^128; not a practical issue.
  No panicking arithmetic on plausible input found.
