issues:
- id: unsafe-without-safety-comments
  severity: low
  comment: |
    No `// SAFETY:` comments anywhere in the source (grep for SAFETY
    returns zero matches). The crate contains ~112 occurrences of
    `unsafe` across src/avx2.rs (63), src/sse41.rs (46), and
    src/guts.rs (3). Most are wrappers around x86 SIMD intrinsics
    (loadu/storeu/add/xor/rot*/etc.), which require both target-feature
    availability and pointer validity for loads/stores. The two
    `#[target_feature(enable = ...)]` entry points (avx2::compress1_loop,
    avx2::compress4_loop, sse41::compress2_loop) are only called from
    guts.rs after `is_x86_feature_detected!` (or static `target_feature`)
    confirms support, but no `// SAFETY:` comment documents this at
    the unsafe call sites (guts.rs:107,121,131). The raw-pointer cast
    in avx2.rs:471 (`&*(input.as_ptr().add(offset) as *const [u8; BLOCKBYTES])`)
    has a narrative comment ("There's guaranteed to be enough input
    because `offset < fin_offset`") that explains the invariant but
    doesn't use the canonical `// SAFETY:` prefix.
- id: no-miri-in-ci
  severity: low
  comment: |
    Upstream CI (.github/workflows/ci.yml on oconnor663/blake2_simd)
    runs cargo tests on stable/beta/nightly across Linux/macOS/Windows
    and cross-tests on i586/i686/armv7/aarch64/powerpc64/s390x, but
    does not invoke `cargo miri test`. Most of the unsafe is x86 SIMD
    intrinsics which miri cannot execute; however, the pointer-arithmetic
    cast in avx2.rs:471 and the `mem::transmute` calls (sse41.rs:286-287,
    avx2.rs:829-830) are miri-testable in principle.
comment: |-
  Pure-Rust BLAKE2b / BLAKE2bp implementation by Jack O'Connor (also
  the author of BLAKE3 and the `blake3` crate). Read every .rs file
  under src/ (lib.rs, guts.rs, portable.rs, avx2.rs, sse41.rs,
  blake2bp.rs, many.rs, test.rs), Cargo.toml, Cargo.toml.orig, and
  README.md.
  
  Supply chain: no build.rs, no proc-macro, three small non-dev
  dependencies (arrayref 0.3.5, arrayvec 0.7 default-features=false,
  constant_time_eq 0.4.2 default-features=false). Grep for
  include_bytes!, std::process, std::net, libc, env::var, Command —
  none present. Licensed MIT, repository link matches GitHub source
  (oconnor663/blake2_simd at rev 6a94ae2e18985c7c35bada8a4d438bfe9ab0d0c0,
  path blake2b/). SIGMA + IV constants in lib.rs match the BLAKE2 spec.
  
  Cap: rating limited to `neutral` because every unsafe block lacks a
  `// SAFETY:` comment. The unsafe is the standard pattern for a
  dynamically-dispatched SIMD hash crate: per-intrinsic `unsafe fn`
  wrappers, plus `#[target_feature]` entry points reached only after
  feature detection in guts::Implementation::detect(). Defensible, but
  uncommented.
  
  Correctness: extensive in-tree tests including BLAKE2 RFC 7693 test
  vectors (EMPTY_HASH, ABC_HASH, ONE_BLOCK_HASH, THOUSAND_HASH), a
  parameterized vector (test_all_parameters), and a separate
  blake2bp::test::test_against_reference cross-checking the optimized
  buffering against a simpler reference. guts.rs::exercise_compress*_loop
  exhaustively exercises serial/parallel strides and finalize/last_node
  combinations across boundary lengths and three counter values
  (including the wrap-near-zero case). Verified the pointer-arithmetic
  cast in avx2.rs:471 — when `offset != fin_offset`, the loop invariant
  `offset < fin_offset <= input.len() - 1` plus
  `padded_blockbytes() >= BLOCKBYTES` guarantees `offset + BLOCKBYTES
  <= input.len()`. No off-by-one, no plausible-input panics, no
  unwraps on parsed data. Count is a u128 so the 2^128-byte BLAKE2b
  spec limit is honored (unlike implementations that cap at u64).
