comment: |-
  Canonical build helper from the rust-lang org (Alex Crichton). Used by
  thousands of crates as a build-dependency to invoke C/C++/asm/CUDA
  compilers. No `build.rs` of its own. Deps: find-msvc-tools, shlex,
  optional jobserver + libc behind `parallel` feature.
  
  Concern #1 (malicious): nothing suspicious. The sole `include_bytes!`
  embeds `src/detect_compiler_family.c` (15 lines of `#ifdef` + `#pragma
  message`) used to probe the configured compiler. Process execution is
  the crate's stated purpose: cc/gcc/clang/cl.exe/ar/xcrun/etc.
  
  Concern #2 (unsafe + SAFETY): caps rating at `neutral`. The custom
  `OnceLock` in `src/utilities.rs` (a stand-in for `std::sync::OnceLock`
  to keep MSRV at 1.63) has several `unsafe` blocks and `unsafe impl
  Sync/Send` lines with no `// SAFETY:` justification - only the Drop
  impl has one (line 125). One block carries an informal
  "Safe b/c checked is_initialized" (line 96), not the canonical form.
  `src/parallel/async_executor.rs` has prose around `Pin::new_unchecked`
  (lines 56-61) explaining the shadowing trick but it isn't labelled
  SAFETY. `src/parallel/stderr.rs` FFI calls to libc::fcntl, libc::ioctl
  and PeekNamedPipe carry no SAFETY comments. The invariants in each
