  digest: Dt4J0ikeiFM_5vo7RyMadKez6Kt0wbRslnWigDD9TQw
review:
  thoroughness: medium
  understanding: high
  rating: positive
comment: |-
  Tiny single-file declarative-macro crate (src/lib.rs, ~380 lines incl. docs).
  Zero runtime/build dependencies, no build.rs, no proc-macro (it is a
  `macro_rules!`), no `unsafe`, no `include_bytes!`, no `Command`, no
  network or filesystem access. Confirmed by reading src/lib.rs and
  tests/test.rs in full and grepping the tree for `unsafe`, FFI, and
  I/O patterns (no hits).
  
  The `cfg_aliases!` macro expands inside the consumer's build.rs and
  emits standard Cargo directives via `println!`:
    - `cargo:rustc-check-cfg=cfg(<alias>)` (lib.rs:368)
    - `cargo:rustc-cfg=<alias>` when the alias's expression evaluates
      truthy (lib.rs:369-371).
  Truth evaluation reads `CARGO_CFG_*` / `CARGO_FEATURE_*` via
  `std::env::var` — the standard Cargo-provided inputs to a build
  script. Nothing else escapes the macro.
  
  Notable, intentional behaviour:
  - DEBUG_ASSERTIONS fallback at lib.rs:184-188 checks `PROFILE ==
    "debug"` because Cargo does not currently set
    `CARGO_CFG_DEBUG_ASSERTIONS`; references rust-lang/cargo#5777.
    Documented and reasonable.
  - README documents two known macro-ergonomics limitations: misuse
    yields cryptic "recursion limit reached" errors, and mutually
    referencing aliases recurse infinitely. Not bugs; documented.
  
  Authorship: Zicklag (katharostech). Repo
  github.com/katharostech/cfg_aliases; license MIT; `passively-maintained`
  per Cargo.toml. The parser is credited to and structurally derived
  from `tectonic_cfg_support::target_cfg!` (NOTICES.md). No advisories
  on rustsec.org for this crate.
  
  No concern-#2 or #3 caps apply (no `unsafe` anywhere). No functional
  bugs found in concern #4.
