comment: |-
  Reviewed const_format 0.2.36, a no_std compile-time string formatting
  library by rodrimati1992. Read every .rs file under src/ (lib.rs, macros/,
  fmt/, wrapper_types/, __str_methods/, __ascii_case_conv/, char_encoding.rs,
  formatting.rs, pargument.rs, slice_cmp.rs, equality.rs, for_assert_macros.rs,
  const_generic_concatcp.rs, __hidden_utils.rs, utils.rs) plus Cargo.toml and
  README.md.
  
  Concern #1 (malicious/suspicious): no build.rs (`build = false`), no
  obfuscation, no Command/syscalls, no network, no env-var reads. Only
  filesystem-touching macro is `include_str!("../../README.md")` gated behind
  the `__test` feature for a doctest. Dependencies are tightly pinned to
  companion crates by the same author (`const_format_proc_macros =0.2.34`,
  `konst 0.2.20`) and the dev-deps `arrayvec` / `fastrand`. License (Zlib),
  repo, docs links all present and consistent.
  
  Concern #2 (unsafe + SAFETY): unsafe usage falls into three patterns —
  (a) `from_utf8_unchecked` on bytes the type invariant guarantees are valid
  UTF-8 (str_writer.rs:352, str_writer_mut.rs:457,480, ascii_str.rs:158);
  (b) `transmute<[[u8; N]; M], [u8; N*M]>` and packed `DecomposedString` casts
  via a `PtrToRef` union to slice/repeat/splice byte arrays at const time
  (macros/str_methods.rs, macros/fmt_macros.rs, macros/map_ascii_case.rs);
  (c) the unsafe fn `StrWriterMut::into_byte_encoding` plus its two call sites
  in fmt/formatter.rs. Each `transmute`/PtrToRef path is preceded by a
  compile-time `_ASSERT_VALID_*` check (length overflow for repeat, char
  boundary for splice/index) so the requested byte ranges land inside the
  source string. `into_byte_encoding` has a "Safety:" doc and Formatter only
  writes valid UTF-8. All substantively sound; the SAFETY-comment style nit
  is captured in `issues` and does not justify capping below `positive`.
  
  Concern #3 (miri): I cannot verify CI from the packaged tarball
  (.github/workflows/ is not included), but `#[cfg(not(miri))]` attributes
  on tests in ascii_str.rs and wrapper_types/pwrapper/tests.rs indicate the
  author is miri-aware. All unsafe in this crate is pure-Rust (no FFI,
  syscalls, or inline asm) and is in principle miri-testable.
  
  Concern #4 (functional correctness): no reproducible bugs found.
  Traced: `str_split!` with empty splitter against the documented
  `"🧡BAR🧠" → ["", "🧡", "B", "A", "R", "🧠", ""]` example; `str_repeat!`
  overflow handling (overflowing_mul + compile-time `assert_valid` panics
  via `[][overflowed_len]`); `is_char_boundary_no_len_check` using
  `(b as i8) >= -0x40`; PWrapper integer length-computation digit thresholds
  (`1_0000_0000 / 100_000_000` match); FOR_ESCAPING table construction asserts
  uniqueness of the 4-low-bit hash. No off-by-one, no panics on plausible
  input, no overflow paths into the unsafe transmutes.
  
  Did not run any code per project rules (no cargo build/test/expand).
