review:
  thoroughness: medium
  understanding: high
  rating: neutral
issues:
- id: unicode-escape-misparsed-after-double-backslash
  severity: medium
  comment: |
    `LitStr::parse_from_literal` in src/parse_utils.rs:198 scans the
    source representation of a string literal for `\u` with
    `match_indices(r#"\u"#)` and does not account for escaped
    backslashes. `formatcp!("\\u")` panics at the
    `value[pos..].find('}').unwrap()` call on line 208; format
    strings of the form `"\\u{N}"` substitute the wrong character
    and then panic in the downstream `parse::<TokenStream2>()`
    unwrap. Reproduction:
    repros/const_format_proc_macros/0.2.34/panic-double-backslash-u/
comment: |-
  Proc-macro implementation crate for `const_format` (companion to
  const_format-0.2.36 which pins this version with `=0.2.34`).
  No `unsafe`, no `build.rs`, no fs/net/env/process I/O, no
  `include_bytes!` blobs. Deps are mainstream: proc-macro2, quote,
  unicode-xid, optional syn. License (Zlib), repo link, and metadata
  are consistent with the published source. Nothing in concern #1.
  
  Concerns #2 and #3 do not apply (no `unsafe`).
  
  Concern #4: there is one functional-correctness bug in
  `LitStr::parse_from_literal` (src/parse_utils.rs:198-223). The code
  scans the *source* representation of a string literal for `\u`
  using `value.match_indices(r#"\u"#)` to expand Rust unicode
  escapes, but does not respect escaped backslashes — an `\u`
  occurring inside `\\u` (an escaped backslash followed by `u`) is
  mistakenly treated as a unicode escape. For the format string
  `"\\u"` the proc-macro panics at `value[pos..].find('}').unwrap()`
  (line 208). For `"\\u{HEX}"` the inner `\u{HEX}` is silently
  substituted with the decoded character, after which the
  re-tokeniser in `StrRawness::tokenize_sub` typically panics on the
  resulting invalid escape. Reachable through any `const_format`
  macro that takes a format string (`formatcp!`, `concatcp!`, etc.).
  
  Caps applied: bug panics on plausible input → at most `neutral`.
  
  Other minor notes (no rating impact): `respan_to_macro::implementation`
  panics on malformed input rather than returning a `compile_error!`;
  `is_path_an_option` indexes `segments[0]` without an explicit
  non-empty check (relies on a syn invariant).
