package:
  source: https://crates.io
  name: constant_time_eq
  version: 0.4.2
  revision: 86f38ed9ad4d0500c5472bb8cb2ddc4fe5ac7143
  digest: yi9Z9B1tcsh2Z1olhC7fNqkN1m90L9kbAmPzDrQ3U_8
review:
  thoroughness: high
  understanding: high
  rating: positive
comment: |-
  Constant-time byte-string equality used widely in the crypto ecosystem.
  Cargo.toml sets `build = false`; no build.rs and no proc-macro. The crate
  is split into a lib.rs dispatcher and four backend modules (classic.rs,
  generic.rs, sse2.rs, neon.rs) plus the aarch64 DIT-bit helper (dit.rs).
  
  Read every .rs file under src/, the tests, the CI workflow, and the
  changelog. Concern walkthrough:
  
  (1) Malicious code: none. Only network/file access in CI is downloading
  toolchains. Inline asm is restricted to register-only constraints
  (`nomem`, `nostack`, `preserves_flags`) on the well-known constant-time
  primitives, plus DIT/SB MSR writes that are conditioned on runtime
  feature detection via `is_aarch64_feature_detected!`.
  
  (2) `unsafe` without SAFETY: every `unsafe` block has a `// SAFETY:`
  comment, and lib.rs has `#![deny(clippy::undocumented_unsafe_blocks)]`
  so the lint enforces it. Each comment names a real invariant (e.g.,
  "all bit patterns are valid for type T" for `read_unaligned`, "called
  only when FEAT_DIT is implemented" for the DIT MSR accessors). The
  `transmute<u8, Features>` in dit.rs is gated on `features > 0` and the
  enum's discriminants are explicit (1, 2, 3); the SAFETY note matches.
  
  (3) Miri: CI runs `cargo miri test` with and without default features.
  Architecture-specific backends are `cfg(not(miri))`-gated, so miri
  exercises the generic backend (which is the one with miri-testable
  `read_unaligned` unsafe). Inline asm + aarch64 system-register access
  are not miri-testable; gating them out is the correct approach.
  
  (4) Correctness: the inputs-equal short-circuit checks `a.len() != b.len()`
  before any timing-sensitive work, matching the documented contract
  (constant-time only when lengths match). All `read_unaligned`
  call-sites assert `src.len() == size_of::<T>()` before the read. The
  generic loop processes word-at-a-time then peels off u128/u64/u32/u16/u8
  tails; size comparisons use `>=` so the residual length is always less
  than the type size before the next branch. The `tests/exhaustive.rs`
  test misaligns the buffer and flips every bit of every position for
  lengths 0..=128 against both the SIMD and generic entry points.
