package:
  source: https://crates.io
  name: criterion
  version: 0.5.1
  revision: dc2b06cd31f7aa34cff6a83a00598e0523186dad
  digest: 36xqKyn8rrqvwoh6ypu-A2GJh4v2jHsigu1mqGMH2-I
review:
  thoroughness: medium
  understanding: medium
  rating: neutral
issues:
- id: is-outlier-inverted-affects-pdf-plots
  severity: low
  comment: |
    stats/univariate/outliers/tukey.rs:241 — `Label::is_outlier()` returns
    true iff the label IS `NotAnOutlier`, opposite of its docstring. The
    "Clean sample" point series in both PDF backends therefore plots
    outliers instead of clean points (plot/gnuplot_backend/pdf.rs:97,
    plot/plotters_backend/pdf.rs:296). Not reproducible via the public
    API because the `stats` module is private; no repro filed.
comment: |-
  Statistics-driven benchmarking library. Read every .rs file under src/
  (~12k LoC across stats, analysis, html, plot, connection, bencher).
  
  Concern #1 (malicious): nothing suspicious. No build.rs, no proc-macros,
  no include_bytes!, no obfuscated strings. Network use is limited to
  TcpStream::connect(("localhost", port)) in lib.rs:128 gated on the
  CARGO_CRITERION_PORT env var — legitimate IPC with the cargo-criterion
  harness. lib.rs:394 shells out to `cargo metadata` to locate the target
  dir; bounded to the cargo binary from $CARGO. Filesystem writes go under
  $CRITERION_HOME / $CARGO_TARGET_DIR / ./target.
  
  Concern #2 (unsafe without SAFETY): 8 unsafe sites, none have a proper
  `// SAFETY:` comment — only freeform NB/FIXME notes:
    - lib.rs:168 ptr::read_volatile in black_box
    - stats/univariate/sample.rs:33,138 mem::transmute(slice/Vec)
    - stats/univariate/percentiles.rs:20 unsafe fn at_unchecked
    - stats/univariate/percentiles.rs:52 caller of at_unchecked
    - stats/univariate/resamples.rs:55 mem::transmute(&[A])
    - stats/mod.rs:84 mem::transmute(slice) in Deref
    - stats/bivariate/mod.rs:141 get_unchecked pair
  Sample<A> is #[repr(transparent)] over [A], so &[A]→&Sample<A> is sound;
  Percentiles<A>(Box<[A]>) and Distribution<A>(Box<[A]>) are tuple structs
  WITHOUT #[repr(transparent)], so transmuting Box<[A]> to Percentiles<A>
  (sample.rs:138) is layout-fragile and only works because rustc currently
  lays out single-field tuple structs identically to the field. Caps rating
  at `neutral` per the reviewer rubric.
  
  Concern #3 (miri): no miri job in .github/workflows or ci/. All the
  unsafe is miri-testable (pure Rust transmute/get_unchecked/read_volatile).
  Independent additional cap at `positive`; subsumed by the #2 cap.
  
  Concern #4 (correctness): one real bug. `Label::is_outlier` in
  stats/univariate/outliers/tukey.rs:241 is `matches!(*self, NotAnOutlier)`,
  but the doc says "Checks if the data point is labeled as an outlier" —
  the implementation is inverted. It is consumed by both PDF plot
  backends (plot/gnuplot_backend/pdf.rs:97,109 and
  plot/plotters_backend/pdf.rs:296) to build the "Clean sample" point
  series, so that series actually plots all outliers and excludes the
  clean data. Only the PDF plots are affected; analysis, CLI, and HTML
  summary output are correct. The bug is not reproducible from outside
  the crate because the `stats` module is private (`mod stats;` in
  lib.rs:74), so no unit-test repro is added. Rating remains `neutral`.
  
  Other notes: `BatchSize::iters_per_batch` (lib.rs:249) uses ceiling
  division `(iters + N - 1) / N` which can overflow for u64::MAX, but
  iter counts in practice are bounded. Lots of unwrap()/expect() but
  mostly on invariants the surrounding code establishes.
