package:
  source: https://crates.io
  name: criterion-plot
  version: 0.5.0
  revision: 5e27b692a43a05736d073fd449e16dcf1c24628c
  digest: fcOOxIvSBcC3--hITVrDMMwr7I-y_ZqjIvmfQwnViis
review:
  thoroughness: medium
  understanding: high
  rating: positive
comment: |-
  Read every `.rs` file under src/ (lib.rs, axis.rs, candlestick.rs, curve.rs,
  data.rs, display.rs, errorbar.rs, filledcurve.rs, grid.rs, key.rs, map.rs,
  prelude.rs, proxy.rs, traits.rs). Read Cargo.toml and README.md. No
  build.rs and no proc-macro (Cargo.toml has no `[lib] proc-macro = true`
  and no `build = ...`).
  
  Concern #1 (malicious/suspicious): nothing flagged. The only process
  invocation is `Command::new("gnuplot")` (lib.rs:546 and lib.rs:991),
  which is the crate's stated purpose. These invoke the bare command name
  `gnuplot` and rely on PATH lookup, conventional for tools that wrap a
  system binary. No network access, no env-var reads, no filesystem
  writes outside the user-supplied `Output` path. Deps are `cast 0.3`
  and `itertools 0.10`, both well-known.
  
  Concern #2/#3 (unsafe / miri): no `unsafe` in the source (grep across
  src/ returned zero hits). No caps apply.
  
  Concern #4 (correctness): minor issues, no exploitable bugs.
  - `Set<Opacity>` (filledcurve.rs:100) doc-comments a panic on values
    outside [0,1] but the impl does not assert; the value is just
    formatted into the gnuplot script. Cosmetic doc/impl mismatch.
  - `Set<FontSize>` (lib.rs:643) asserts `size >= 0.` while doc says
    "non-positive" panics — 0.0 is allowed despite the wording.
  - Output path is escaped for single quotes (lib.rs:449), but labels,
    titles, axis labels, and font names are interpolated directly into
    single-quoted gnuplot strings without escaping. An apostrophe in a
    user-supplied label would break the gnuplot script. Not a security
    issue — output is piped to a local gnuplot process under the user's
    control, and inputs come from the consumer's own code.
  
  README notes the crate is "looking for a maintainer"; treat as
  effectively unmaintained. It is an implementation detail of
  criterion.rs and pinned by that crate's releases.
