package:
  source: https://crates.io
  name: crossbeam-deque
  version: 0.8.6
  revision: ccd83ac4108a2a1b41e9c6e79c87267167d18dfa
  digest: juR7i4yXO0Rda1RGHtMFQe8tpLqRJ190kRs5V0-KhXA
review:
  thoroughness: medium
  understanding: medium
  rating: neutral
comment: |-
  Concurrent work-stealing deques (Chase-Lev Worker/Stealer + an Injector
  MPMC FIFO). Two source files: src/lib.rs (~110 lines, no_std + std mod
  re-exports) and src/deque.rs (~2.2k lines). Read both end to end and
  scanned the four test files. No build.rs, no proc-macros, no
  include_bytes!, no network/process/libc usage. Cargo.toml is clean —
  only depends on the sibling crossbeam-epoch and crossbeam-utils crates
  (default-features disabled, std feature opt-in), plus rand as a
  dev-dep. License MIT/Apache-2.0, repository points to the canonical
  crossbeam-rs org. Algorithm matches the published Chase-Lev and Le et
  al. weak-memory papers cited at deque.rs:99.
  
  Concern #2 (SAFETY comments): the file contains 42 unsafe occurrences
  but only two explicit `// SAFETY:` headers (deque.rs:1239 and 1245, on
  Block::new). The remaining unsafe blocks (Buffer::at/read/write,
  resize, all the Stealer/Injector steal paths, the Drop impls) carry
  free-form rationale in surrounding comments rather than the canonical
  `// SAFETY:` form. The invariants ARE the ones from the cited Chase-
  Lev / weak-memory papers, but per the rubric the missing-SAFETY-header
  cap applies — capping at `neutral`.
  
  Concern #3 (miri): the published tarball doesn't ship .github/, so I
  can't confirm CI config directly, but every test file is written with
  `#[cfg(miri)]` arms that shrink iteration counts and a `cfg_attr(miri,
  ignore)` on the heavy stress tests — strong evidence the project does
  run these under miri. Cargo.toml's check-cfg also lists
  `crossbeam_loom` and `crossbeam_sanitize`, consistent with the
  crossbeam org's known loom/miri practice. No additional cap from #3.
  
  Concern #4: read the steal and pop paths critically. Index arithmetic
  uses wrapping_{add,sub} on isize/usize as expected; bounds checks on
  buffer slots come from masking with `cap-1` (cap is power-of-two,
  asserted in Buffer::alloc). Volatile read/write on possibly-racing
  slots is documented at lines 70-86 as a deliberate hack to avoid
  per-T atomic stores. The CHANGELOG notes 0.8.6 fixed a stack-overflow
  on pushing very large `T` into Injector (#1146/#1147/#1159); inspecting
  Block::new at deque.rs:1238 confirms it now uses alloc_zeroed +
  handle_alloc_error rather than `Box::new(zeroed)`, which is the fix.
  No new functional bugs surfaced during the read.
