review:
  thoroughness: medium
  understanding: high
  rating: positive
comment: |-
  Tiny crate (one src/lib.rs that is just `include!(...)`) that generates a
  `unroll!` macro_rules! definition at build time from build.rs. No
  dependencies. License MIT. Repository link matches the author's GitHub.
  
  Concern #1 (malicious/suspicious): build.rs reads OUT_DIR, writes a single
  generated `lib.rs` under it, and emits exactly one cargo directive
  (`cargo:rustc-env=CRUNCHY_LIB_SUFFIX=<sep>lib.rs`). No network, no shelling
  out, no env-var probing, no writes outside OUT_DIR. The included file is
  pulled in via `include!(concat!(env!("OUT_DIR"), env!("CRUNCHY_LIB_SUFFIX")))`
  in src/lib.rs:36 — slightly more convoluted than the usual
  `include!(concat!(env!("OUT_DIR"), "/lib.rs"))` pattern, but not malicious;
  it splits the path separator via `std::path::MAIN_SEPARATOR`.
  
  Concerns #2 and #3 (unsafe / miri): No `unsafe` anywhere — grep is clean.
  
  Concern #4 (correctness): The macro logic is straightforward. The empty
  range `0..0` is handled explicitly by the first rule producing nothing.
  Non-zero starts go through a `@`-helper that emits N const-bound iterations
  guarded by a `$v >= $start` check; step_by is converted to a contiguous
  index range with a multiplicative remapping. Ranges above the compile-time
  cap (default 128, configurable 64/256/512/1024/2048) fail to expand —
  documented behavior.
  
  Minor: the crate-level doc in src/lib.rs says the default limit is 64,
  while Cargo.toml's `default = ["limit_128"]` and README both say 128 —
  doc drift only, no behavior impact.
