review:
  thoroughness: high
  understanding: high
  rating: strong
comment: |-
  Tiny (~312 LoC, single src/lib.rs) RustCrypto trait crate. Provides the
  common traits (`BlockSizeUser`, `KeySizeUser`, `IvSizeUser`, `OutputSizeUser`,
  `KeyInit`, `KeyIvInit`, `InnerInit`, `InnerIvInit`, `Reset`,
  `AlgorithmName`, `ParBlocksSizeUser`) and associated type aliases that the
  entire RustCrypto stack (block ciphers, AEADs, hashes) builds on. The 0.1.7
  bump is a single change vs 0.1.6: pin `generic-array` to `=0.14.7`
  (CHANGELOG.md, PR #2088) to avoid a SemVer-incompatible jump in transitive
  consumers.
  
  Concern #1 (malicious/suspicious): no build.rs (`build = false` at
  Cargo.toml:17), no proc-macro, no `include_bytes!`, no `std::process`,
  no network or filesystem I/O, no obfuscation. Three direct dependencies:
  `generic-array =0.14.7` (RustCrypto), `typenum 1.14` (RustCrypto-adjacent,
  paholg), and optional `rand_core 0.6` (RustCrypto). License is
  `MIT OR Apache-2.0`; repository link (github.com/RustCrypto/traits) and
  authors ("RustCrypto Developers") match the published crate metadata.
  
  Concern #2 (unsafe + SAFETY): N/A. `#![forbid(unsafe_code)]` at
  src/lib.rs:9; `rg unsafe` across the source returns only that forbid
  attribute.
  
  Concern #3 (miri): N/A — no unsafe code anywhere in the crate.
  
  Concern #4 (correctness): the crate is almost entirely trait
  declarations with default-method bodies. The three fallible default
  methods all length-check before calling the infallible variant:
  - `KeyInit::new_from_slice` (lib.rs:129-135) compares `key.len()` to
    `Self::KeySize::to_usize()`, returns `Err(InvalidLength)` on mismatch.
  - `KeyIvInit::new_from_slices` (lib.rs:155-166) checks both `key.len()`
    and `iv.len()` against the respective associated-type sizes.
  - `InnerIvInit::inner_iv_slice_init` (lib.rs:214-220) checks
    `iv.len()` against `Self::IvSize::to_usize()`.
  The `*_from_slice` functions on `GenericArray` panic if the slice is
  the wrong length, but each call site here is gated by the explicit
  length check immediately above, so the panic path is unreachable from
  the public API. The `generate_key` / `generate_iv` helpers
  (lib.rs:141-145, 172-186, 226-230) call `rng.fill_bytes` on a
  zero-initialized `GenericArray` — correct usage of the `RngCore` API.
  Blanket impls of `KeySizeUser`/`KeyInit`/`KeyIvInit` for `InnerUser`
  / `InnerInit` / `InnerIvInit` types (lib.rs:233-273) just forward to
  the inner type's impl; no panics, no surprises. No `unwrap`/`expect`,
  no arithmetic, no indexing. No reproducible bugs found.
  
  Did NOT run any code (no cargo build/test/expand) per project rules.
