  Servo's CSS Syntax Level 3 tokenizer/parser. No build.rs (build = false in
  Cargo.toml). No proc-macro in this crate (cssparser-macros is a separate
  dependency, not reviewed here). No suspicious I/O, network, process
  execution, or include_bytes! of opaque blobs in src/ (only include_str! of
  JSON test fixtures inside #[cfg(test)] in tests.rs).
  
  Read every file under src/ (lib.rs, macros.rs, parser.rs, tokenizer.rs,
  rules_and_declarations.rs, serializer.rs, color.rs, cow_rc_str.rs,
  from_bytes.rs, nth.rs, unicode_range.rs). Public-input parsing paths in
  consume_numeric, consume_string, consume_unquoted_url, consume_escape,
  unicode_range::parse_concatenated, color::parse_hash_color, and nth.rs
  look sound: integer math is f64-bounded and saturated when narrowing to
  i32 (tokenizer.rs:1095), and unicode_range checks range.end <=
  char::MAX (unicode_range.rs:52). consume_hex caps at 6 digits so the
  shift in parse_concatenated cannot exceed 24 bits.
  
  Unsafe usage (cap-driving finding): roughly 20 unsafe blocks across
  cow_rc_str.rs, tokenizer.rs, serializer.rs and macros.rs. Several have
  no `// SAFETY:` comment at all (cow_rc_str.rs:47/64/77/92/106/116,
  tokenizer.rs:323/432, serializer.rs:180/188); others have nearby
  prose explaining the invariant ("string_bytes is well-formed UTF-8…",
  the layout-equivalence comments in macros.rs:181-194, the explicit
  SAFETY block in macros.rs:135-139) but don't use the canonical
  `// SAFETY:` prefix. The invariants stated, where given, are plausible:
  CowRcStr maintains a Rc<String>/&'a str union discriminated by
  borrowed_len_or_max == usize::MAX (documented on the struct), and
  from_utf8_release_unchecked is gated to debug-checked in
  cfg!(debug_assertions). Per AGENTS.md concern #2 this caps at
  `neutral`.
  
  Concern #3 (miri): CI runs `cargo miri test --features skip_long_tests`
  on nightly across the no-feature / dummy_match_byte / malloc_size_of
  configurations (.github/workflows/main.yml:66-68), which exercises the
  unsafe code paths. No miri cap applied.
  
  Concern #4 (functional bugs): no reproducible bug found on this pass.
