review:
  thoroughness: medium
  understanding: high
  rating: positive
comment: |-
  Tiny (~190 lines, single lib.rs) proc-macro crate from Servo providing two
  macros used by `cssparser`: `_cssparser_internal_max_len!` and `match_byte!`.
  
  Concern #1 (malicious code): clean. No build.rs. proc-macro = true but the
  macro bodies do nothing beyond parsing tokens with `syn`, building a 256-byte
  lookup table, and emitting tokens via `quote`. No filesystem, network,
  process, env, or include_bytes! usage (grep clean). Deps are `syn` and
  `quote`, both ecosystem-standard. License MPL-2.0, repo points to
  servo/rust-cssparser.
  
  Concern #2/#3 (unsafe): no `unsafe` anywhere -- both caps N/A.
  
  Concern #4 (correctness): reviewed both macros.
  - `_cssparser_internal_max_len`: validates each string literal is ASCII
    lowercase, tracks max length. Straightforward.
  - `match_byte`: builds a [u8; 256] dispatch table from match-arm byte
    patterns (Lit, Range, Wild, Ident, Or). Range handling at lib.rs:72-83
    iterates `lo..hi` then sets `hi` separately, i.e. always inclusive. This
    ignores the `PatRange.limits` field, but Rust match patterns only accept
    `..=` on stable, so in practice the behavior matches user intent. The
    `panic!`/`unreachable!`/`assert!` calls (lib.rs:46, 54, 92, 106, 144-148)
    fire at macro-expansion time on malformed input -- produces a compile
    error rather than a clean syn::Error::new, slightly worse UX but not a
    correctness bug. `case_id as u8` at line 167 would wrap if a match had
    >255 arms, but byte matches with that many arms are implausible.
  
  No issues warranting an `issues:` block. Comfortable depending on this.
