comment: |-
  Companion proc-macro crate to `arbitrary`, implementing `#[derive(Arbitrary)]`.
  Authored by the rust-fuzz project (fitzgen, manishearth, et al.).
  
  Read in full: Cargo.toml (proc-macro = true, deps = proc-macro2/quote/syn
  only), README, and all four source files: src/lib.rs (517 lines),
  src/container_attributes.rs, src/field_attributes.rs,
  src/variant_attributes.rs.
  
  Concern checks:
  1. Malicious/suspicious: no build.rs; no `unsafe`, `include_bytes!`,
     `std::process`, `libc`, network, or filesystem APIs (grep confirmed
     only URL/comment hits). The proc-macro body purely transforms a
     DeriveInput into a tokenized `impl Arbitrary` via syn/quote — no
     side effects at macro-expansion time. Deps are the canonical
     proc-macro trio at recent, well-known versions.
  2. unsafe without SAFETY: no unsafe present.
  3. miri coverage: N/A (no unsafe).
  4. Functional correctness: straightforward derive plumbing. Variant
     indexing uses the standard multiply-shift ranged-random trick
     (Lemire); `(u32 * count) >> 32 < count` makes the `unreachable!()`
     arm sound. `variants.len() as u64` is fine — proc-macro inputs cap
     at a few thousand variants in practice. `f.ident.as_ref().unwrap()`
     in `construct` is gated by `Fields::Named`. Attribute parsing
     errors propagate via `syn::Error` rather than panicking.
  
  No issues to file. License MIT OR Apache-2.0, repository link present
  and active.
