review:
  thoroughness: medium
  understanding: high
  rating: positive
comment: |-
  Proc-macro implementation half of `derive_more` 2.1.1 (companion crate
  reviewed positive). 12.4k LOC across src/, authored by Jelte Fennema,
  MIT, repo https://github.com/JelteF/derive_more. `proc-macro = true`, so
  this code runs at compile-time inside every downstream consumer's
  `cargo build` -- that is the threat surface.
  
  Concern #1 (malicious/suspicious): clean. No `build.rs` (`build = false`
  in Cargo.toml; the leftover `build-dependencies.rustc_version = "0.4"`
  is dead -- no build script exists to invoke it). No `std::process`,
  `Command`, network APIs (`TcpStream`, `reqwest`, etc.), `libc`,
  `env::var`/`env!`, filesystem writes, `transmute`, inline asm, or
  `#[no_mangle]`/`extern "C"` anywhere in src/. `include_str!` is used
  twice (lib.rs:1 for README, lib.rs:94 for per-feature `doc/*.md`),
  both literal paths into bundled doc/ -- emitted as proc-macro rustdoc.
  No obfuscation: no large byte blobs, no base64/hex-encoded blobs.
  Runtime deps are the canonical proc-macro trio plus two optional
  helpers: proc-macro2 1.0, quote 1.0, syn 2.0.45, optional
  convert_case 0.10 and unicode-xid 0.2.2.
  
  Concern #2 (unsafe + SAFETY): `#![forbid(non_ascii_idents, unsafe_code)]`
  at lib.rs:5 statically forbids `unsafe` in the macro's own code. The
  only `unsafe` token in src/ is at cmp/partial_eq.rs:186, INSIDE a
  `quote!` block (emitted into consumer code, not executed by the macro):
  `_ => unsafe { derive_more::core::hint::unreachable_unchecked() }`.
  Has a proper preceding `// SAFETY:` comment naming the invariant. The
  emitted arm is only inserted when `self.variants.len() > 1` and
  `no_fields_arm.is_none()`, and the surrounding generated `PartialEq`
  impl always emits a `mem::discriminant(self) == mem::discriminant(__other)`
  short-circuit ahead of the match -- so the `_` wildcard is genuinely
  unreachable in the expanded code. No cap from #2.
  
  Concern #3 (miri): N/A -- the proc-macro itself executes no unsafe
  code. Miri coverage of the quoted `unreachable_unchecked` belongs to
  consumer crates, not this one.
  
  Concern #4 (functional correctness): no reproducible bugs found.
  Audited utils.rs (attribute parsing helpers), fmt/parsing.rs (1302-
  line hand-rolled format-string parser), parsing.rs, error.rs, from.rs,
  into.rs, from_str.rs, ops/*, fmt/*, and grep-scanned all 36 .rs files.
  The format-string parser uses `c.len_utf8()` for byte-index slicing
  and derives all tail slices from suffix cursors of the original input,
  so no UTF-8 boundary panic risk; it has extensive inline unit tests.
  Several `panic!`/`unimplemented!()` sites on malformed attribute input
  (utils.rs:130/263/400/609/664, deref.rs:13, deref_mut.rs:13,
  not_like.rs:28/34, constructor.rs:24, etc.) abort the consumer's build
  with a raw panic instead of a span-tagged `syn::Error` -- rough
  diagnostics but not a soundness or supply-chain issue. lib.rs:96
  `syn::parse(input).unwrap()` similarly panics on unparseable derive
  input that rustc has already filtered. All other `.unwrap()`s reviewed
  are guarded by prior filter/length checks.
  
  Did NOT run any code (no cargo build/test/expand) per project rules.
